.NET MAUI has built-in APIs for all three needs:

**Detect current theme:**
```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

**Subscribe to real-time changes:**
```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");

    // Update UI on main thread
    MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() =>
    {
        // e.g. swap colors, refresh styles
    });
};
```

**Force a specific theme (overrides system setting):**
```csharp
// Lock to dark mode regardless of device setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Typical wiring in `App.xaml.cs`:**
```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Debug.WriteLine($"System theme → {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // UserAppTheme is AppTheme.Unspecified here means we follow system;
        // if user forced a theme, this event still fires but UserAppTheme wins.
    }
}
```

**XAML-side adaptive resources** (no code needed):
```xml
<ContentPage.Resources>
    <Color x:Key="PageBg">
        <AppThemeBinding Light="White" Dark="#1E1E1E" />
    </Color>
</ContentPage.Resources>

<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{StaticResource PageBg}" />
```

`AppThemeBinding` automatically reacts to theme changes — both system-driven and `UserAppTheme`-driven — so for simple color/style swaps you don't need the event at all. Use the event for side-effects like logging or non-UI work.
